{"request_date":"2014-04-03 18:26:20.849","search_value":1046,"search_type":"id","results":{"region":"Region 11","displayDate":"1935","objectNumber":"FA546-A","ObjTextEntries":[{"id":10611,"objectId":1046,"textType":"Description","textEntry":"See Section Bulletin 2, pg 3-5 and Bulletin 14, pg. 14 for additional information.<BR>For DOJ competition details, see Bulletin 2, pages 8-10.<BR><BR>Plaque text prepared for DOJ Spring 2002: (no plaque made at that time):<BR><BR>The Department of the Treasury's Section of Painting and Sculpture awarded the commission for the two lunettes in the Attorney General's conference room to Leon Kroll in 1935.&nbsp; In the mural Justice Triumphant, a white-robed female figure representing Justice is paired with a black-robed Judge signifying Law, who extends a hand to the figures gathered below him.&nbsp; This group represents the underprivileged citizens of the world who are protected and elevated by Justice and Law.&nbsp; Kroll modeled the features of the figure of Law on Harlan Fiske Stone, the Supreme Court Justice (1925-46) and former Attorney General (1924-25), whose face the artist believed to be appropriately \"solid, strong, and intelligent\" for the subject matter of the mural.<BR><BR>Justice Defeated represents the tragedy and havoc caused by the absence of Justice, feelings communicated to the viewer by the barren landscape and the threatening sky.&nbsp; Justice is presented as a recumbent woman in white who has been overwhelmed by a black-robed figure whose serene and innocuous mask hides his face, which is cold, cruel and vicious.&nbsp; Kroll used \"brute force and fear as the dominant motif\" in this panel and he believed that upon seeing the plight of the \"lovely\" figure of Justice, any Attorney General would be galvanized to fight for \"her\" survival.&nbsp; Initially the Advisory Commission felt that Justice Defeated was too violent, but were eventually persuaded to approve Kroll's design which both Attorney General Homer S. Cummings (1933-39) and the Supervising Architect of the Justice building supported.<BR><BR>&nbsp; <BR>"},{"id":33240,"objectId":1046,"textType":"Medium","textEntry":"Oil on canvas"}],"ObjectsPeople":[{"id":2630,"objectId":1046,"personId":3331,"role":"Associated Program","displayName":"New Deal Fine Arts","institution":"New Deal Fine Arts"},{"lastName":"Kroll","id":25823,"objectId":1046,"personId":1722,"role":"Artist","displayName":"Leon Kroll","firstName":"Leon"}],"medium":"oil on canvas","primaryImage":"/FA546/Carol Highsmith/Kroll, L- FA546-A.01.CH2007.jpg","id":1046,"title":"JUSTICE TRIUMPHANT","classification":"painting","artistRelatedObjects":[{"region":"Region 11","displayDate":"1935","objectNumber":"FA546-B","medium":"oil on canvas","primaryImage":"/FA546/Carol Highsmith/Kroll, L- FA546-B.CH2007.jpg","id":402,"title":"JUSTICE DEFEATED","classification":"painting","dimensions":"7'9\" x 21'8\"","artist":"Leon Kroll"},{"region":"Central Office","displayDate":"1938","objectNumber":"FA4698","medium":"oil on board","id":2668,"title":"DEFEAT OF JUSTICE","classification":"painting","creditLine":"Loan from the Fine Arts Program, Public Buildings Service, U.S. General Services Administration\r\nCommissioned through the Section of Fine Arts, 1934-1943\r\n","dimensions":"Canvas: 18 3/8 x 44 1/8 in. (46.7 x 112.1 cm)\r\nFramed: 35 3/8 x 55 3/8 in. (89.9 x 140.7 cm)","artist":"Leon Kroll"},{"region":"Central Office","displayDate":"1938","objectNumber":"FA4699","medium":"oil on board","id":2669,"title":"TRIUMPH OF JUSTICE","classification":"painting","creditLine":"Loan from the Fine Arts Program, Public Buildings Service, U.S. General Services Administration\r\nCommissioned through the Section of Fine Arts, 1934-1943\r\n","dimensions":"Canvas: 18 3/8 x 44 in. (46.7 x 111.8 cm)\r\nFramed: 35 1/4 x 55 3/8 in. (89.5 x 140.7 cm)","artist":"Leon Kroll"}],"siteRelatedObjects":[{"region":"Region 11","displayDate":"1933","objectNumber":"FA4073-A","medium":"limestone","id"